      <section name='plaque'>

         <para number='1' comment='read the plaque'>
         This room has been constructed from the plans for a giant steam driven orrery prepared for Victorian industrialist Raymond Skeffington Quick-Manning.
         </para>

         <para number='2'>
         Quick-Manning, whose fortune came from the invention of an efficient mines water pump started building the orrery in the grounds of his mansion near Black Dyke Mills.
         </para>

         <para number='3'>
         Unfortunately, the escalating cost of the construction drove Quick-Manning deep into debt, and he died of a heart attack while attending a creditors meeting.
         </para>

         <para number='4'>
         The orrery was abandoned only partially constructed, and the ruins, particularly the machine room with its tall chimney, became known to the locals as "Manning's Folly".
         </para>

         <para number='5'>
         The room is as faithful a replica of the orrery as is possible within a closed environment.
         </para>

         <para number='6'>
         The main changes are the substitution of modern lighting for gas lights and the heating of the steam boiler is by electricity rather than coal. In addition, the materials used in the construction of the orrery have been brought up to modern safety standards, and some of the heavenly bodies discovered after Quick-Manning's death have been added.
         </para>

      </section>

